brings to light the unstudied folk perspectives on the foundational myth of Mysore and its urban history. Singing the Goddess into Place demonstrates how folk narratives reflect local context while also actively working to upend social inequities based on caste and ritual/devotional practices. By delving into this world, the book helps us understand how a landscape is transformed through people's relationship with it and how this relationship helps build meaning for the communities that call it home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aHindu goddesseszIndiazKarnataka. 0aHindu musiczIndiazKarnataka. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women in Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848867740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438488677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438488677/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles